# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lonworks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lonworks/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:lonworks/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:lonworks/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Echelon was founded in February 1988 in Palo Alto, California by Clifford "Mike" Markkula Jr.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Echelon's LonWorks platform for control networking was released in 1990 for use in the building, industrial, transportation, and home automation markets.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Started in 2003, Echelon's Networked Energy Services system was an open metering service.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Echelon provides the underlying network technology for the world's largest Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) in Italy with over 27 million connected electricity meters.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Based on the experiences with this installation, Echelon developed the NES (Networked Energy Services) System (including smart meters, data concentrators and a head-end data collection system) in October 2014 with about 3.5 million devices installed.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] In August 2014, after quarterly revenues dropped from $24.8 million to $15 million, Echelon announced it was leaving the smart-grid business, shifting its entire corporate focus to the Internet of things as a market for its technology.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Echelon committed to only support existing customers, but not grow the grid business, and to potentially seek the sale of its grid business.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] Echelon is based in Santa Clara, California, with international offices in China, France, Germany, Italy, Hong Kong, Japan, Korea, The Netherlands, and the United Kingdom.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] On June 29, 2018, Adesto Technologies announced its intention to acquire Echelon for $45 million.
[src:lonworks/echelon-corporation] The acquisition was completed on September 14, 2018.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:lonworks/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:lonworks/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:lonworks/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:lonworks/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] The technology had its origins with chip designs, power lines, twisted pairs, signaling technology, routers, network management software, and other products from Echelon Corporation.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (**ANSI/CEA-709.1-B**).
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Echelon's power line and twisted pair signaling technology were also submitted to ANSI for standardization and acceptance.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] In 2008, ISO and IEC granted the communications protocol, twisted pair signaling technology, power line signaling technology, and Internet Protocol (IP) compatibility standard numbers ISO/IEC 14908-1, -2, -3, and -4.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] By 2010, approximately 90 million devices were installed with LonWorks technology.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Manufacturers in a variety of industries including building, home, street lighting, transportation, utility, and industrial automation have adopted the platform as the basis for their product and service offerings.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Two physical-layer signaling technologies, twisted pair *free topology* and power-line carrier, are typically included in each of the standards created around the LonWorks technology.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] The two-wire layer operates at 78 kbit/s using differential Manchester encoding, while the power line achieves either 5.4 or 3.6 kbit/s, depending on frequency.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Additionally, the LonWorks platform uses an affiliated IP tunneling standard—ISO/IEC 14908-4 (ANSI/CEA-852)—in use by a number of manufacturers to connect the devices on previously deployed and new LonWorks platform-based networks to IP-aware applications or remote network-management tools.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Many LonWorks platform-based control applications are being implemented with some sort of IP integration, either at the UI/application level or in the controls infrastructure.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] This is accomplished with Web services or IP-routing products available in the market.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] An Echelon Corporation-designed IC consisting of several 8-bit processors, the *Neuron chip* was initially the only way to implement a LonTalk protocol node and is used in the large majority of LonWorks platform-based hardware.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Since 1999, the protocol has been available for general-purpose processors: A port of the ANSI/CEA-709.1 standard to IP-based or 32-bit chips.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] As of 14 September, 2018, Echelon Corporation was acquired by Adesto Technologies Corporation.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] Adesto was then acquired by Dialog Semiconductor who were then acquired by Renesas Electronics.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] As of 2024, Renesas continues to offer LonWorks (and BACnet) products.
[src:lonworks/lonworks] One of the keys to the interoperability of the system is the standardisation of the variables used to describe physical things to LonWorks.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A wide range of power-line communication technologies is needed for different applications, ranging from home automation to Internet access, which is often called broadband over power lines (BPL).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Most PLC technologies limit themselves to one type of wiring (such as premises wiring within a single building), but some can cross between two levels (for example, both the distribution network and premises wiring).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Typically, transformers prevent the propagation of the signal, which requires multiple technologies to form very large networks.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Various data rates and frequencies are used in different situations.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A number of difficult technical problems are common between wireless and power-line communication, notably those of spread spectrum radio signals operating in a crowded environment.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Radio interference, for example, has long been a concern of amateur radio groups.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Appearing as early as 1925, carrier equipment for power lines was designed for use by electric utility companies to facilitate communication with technicians operating high voltage electrical equipment, which was often located hundreds of miles away from existing telephone infrastructure.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Instead of running new dedicated telephone wires to remote locations, carrier equipment could be used to transmit telephone signals over high voltage power lines rated up to 220,000 volts.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] High-voltage carrier equipment was installed by electricians, and low-voltage carrier equipment was installed by phone technicians.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The M carrier system was one of a series of early carrier systems developed by AT&T for long-distance communications.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] M1 carrier equipment was designed for use with rural 7,200 volt power lines and could be installed without disrupting power to the grid.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] By 1953 the Bell System had almost 10,000 M1 carrier stations in service.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power-line communications systems operate by adding a modulated carrier signal to the wiring system.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Different types of power-line communications use different frequency bands.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Since the power distribution system was originally intended for transmission of AC power at typical frequencies of 50 or 60 Hz, power wire circuits have only a limited ability to carry higher frequencies.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The propagation problem is a limiting factor for each type of power-line communications.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The main issue determining the frequencies of power-line communication is laws that limit interference with radio services.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Wiring for power transmission typically uses unshielded cable.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The unshielded cable may cause radio interference when the cable is used for high-frequency data signals; see Electromagnetic shielding for details.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Many nations regulate unshielded wired emissions as if they were radio transmitters.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These jurisdictions usually require unlicensed uses to be below 500 kHz or in unlicensed radio bands.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Some jurisdictions (such as the EU), regulate wire-line transmissions further.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The U.S. is a notable exception, permitting limited-power wide-band signals to be injected into unshielded wiring, as long as the wiring is not designed to propagate radio waves in free space.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Data rates and distance limits vary widely over many power-line communication standards.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Low-frequency (about 100–200 kHz) carriers impressed on high-voltage transmission lines may carry one or two analog voice circuits, or telemetry and control circuits with an equivalent data rate of a few hundred bits per second; however, these circuits may be many miles long.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Higher data rates generally imply shorter ranges; a local area network operating at millions of bits per second may only cover one floor of an office building, but eliminates the need for installation of dedicated network cabling.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Although different protocols and legislation exist throughout the world, there are basically only two types of PLC: the *indoor* PLC and the *outdoor* PLC.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Ripple control adds an audio-frequency tone to an AC line.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Typical frequencies are from 100 to 2400 Hz.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Each district usually has its own frequency, so that adjacent areas are unaffected.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Codes are sent by slowly turning the tone on and off.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Equipment at a customer site receives the codes and turns customer equipment off and on.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Often, the decoder is part of a standard electricity meter, and controls relays.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] There are also utility codes, e.g., to set the clocks of the power meters at midnight.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In this way, the utility can avoid up to 20% of capital expenses for generating equipment.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This lowers costs for electricity and fuel usage.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Brownouts and rolling blackouts are more easily prevented.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Grids that use cogeneration can enable auxiliary customer equipment when the generators are being run to generate heat rather than electricity.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] An annoyance for customers is that sometimes the code to turn equipment on is lost, or load shedding is inconvenient or dangerous.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] For example, during a party, a dangerous heat wave or when life-preserving medical equipment is on-site.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] To handle these cases, some equipment includes switches to circumvent load shedding.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Some meters switch into a higher billing rate when the *party switch* is flipped.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Utility companies use special coupling capacitors to connect radio transmitters and receivers to the AC power-carrying conductors.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power meters often use small transformers with linear amplifiers in the range of tens of watts.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Most of the expense of any PLC system is the power electronics.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] By comparison, the electronics to encode and decode is usually small, in a special-purpose integrated circuit.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Thus, even the complicated OFDM standards can still be economical.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Frequencies used are in the range of 24 to 500 kHz, with transmitter power levels up to hundreds of watts.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These signals may be impressed on one conductor, on two conductors or on all three conductors of a high-voltage AC transmission line.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Several PLC channels may be coupled onto one high-voltage line.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Filtering devices are applied at substations to prevent the carrier frequency current from being bypassed through the station apparatus and to ensure that distant faults do not affect the isolated segments of the PLC system.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These circuits are used for control of switchgear and for protection of transmission lines.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] For example, a protective relay can use a PLC channel to trip a line if a fault is detected between its two terminals, but to leave the line in operation if the fault is elsewhere on the system.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] To sectionalize the transmission network and protect against failures, a *wave trap* is connected in series with the power (transmission) line.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] They consist of one or more sections of resonant circuits, which block the high-frequency carrier waves (24–500 kHz) and let power frequency current (50–60 Hz) pass through.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Wave traps are used in the switchyards of most power stations to prevent carriers from entering the station equipment.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Each wave trap has a lightning arrester to protect it from surge voltages.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A coupling capacitor is used to connect the transmitters and receivers to the high-voltage line.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This provides a low-impedance path for carrier energy to the high-voltage line but blocks the power frequency circuit by being a high-impedance path.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The coupling capacitor may be part of a capacitor voltage transformer used for voltage measurement.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power-line carrier systems have long been a favorite at many utilities because they allow them to reliably move data over an infrastructure that they control.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A *PLC carrier repeating station* is a facility at which a PLC signal on a power line is refreshed.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Therefore, the signal is filtered out from the power line, demodulated and modulated on a new carrier frequency, and then injected into the power line again.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] As PLC signals can span long distances (several hundred kilometers), such facilities only exist on very long power lines using PLC equipment.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power-line carrier communication (PLCC) is mainly used for telecommunication, tele-protection and tele-monitoring between electrical substations through power lines at high voltages, such as 110 kV, 220 kV, 400 kV.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The modulation generally used in these systems is amplitude modulation.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The carrier frequency range is used for audio signals, protection and a pilot frequency.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The pilot frequency is a signal in the audio range that is transmitted continuously for failure detection.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The voice signal is compressed and filtered into the 300 to 4000 Hz range, and this audio frequency is mixed with the carrier frequency.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The carrier frequency is again filtered, amplified and transmitted.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The transmission power of these HF carrier frequencies will be in the range of 0 to +32 dbW.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This range is set according to the distance between substations.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] PLCC can be used for interconnecting private branch exchanges (PBXs).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] PLC is one of the technologies used for automatic meter reading.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Both one-way and two-way systems have been successfully used for decades.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Interest in this application has grown substantially in recent history, not so much because there is an interest in automating a manual process, but because there is an interest in obtaining fresh data from all metered points in order to better control and operate the system.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] PLC is one of the technologies being used in Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In a one-way (inbound only) system, readings bubble up from end devices (such as meters), through the communication infrastructure, to a *master station* which publishes the readings.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A one-way system might be lower-cost than a two-way system, but it is difficult to reconfigure should the operating environment change.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In a two-way system (supporting both outbound and inbound), commands can be broadcast out from the master station to end devices (meters) – allowing for reconfiguration of the network, or to obtain readings, or to convey messages, etc.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The device at the end of the network may then respond (inbound) with a message that carries the desired value.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Outbound messages injected at a utility substation will propagate to all points downstream.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This type of broadcast allows the communication system to simultaneously reach many thousands of devices—all of which are known to have power, and have been previously identified as candidates for load shedding.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] PLC also may be a component of a smart grid.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These systems are often used in countries in which it is illegal to transmit signals that interfere with normal radio.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power-line communications technology can use the electrical power wiring within a home for home automation: for example, remote control of lighting and appliances without installation of additional control wiring.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Typically, home-control power-line communication devices operate by modulating in a carrier wave of between 20 and 200 kHz into the household wiring at the transmitter.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The carrier is modulated by digital signals.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Each receiver in the system has an address and can be individually commanded by the signals transmitted over the household wiring and decoded at the receiver.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These devices may be either plugged into regular power outlets or permanently wired in place.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Since the carrier signal may propagate to nearby homes (or apartments) on the same distribution system, these control schemes have a *house address* that designates the owner.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A popular technology known as X10 has been used since the 1970s.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The universal powerline bus, introduced in 1999, uses pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The physical layer method is a very different scheme than the X10.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] LonTalk, part of the LonWorks home automation product line, was accepted as part of some automation standards.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Narrowband power-line communications began soon after electrical service became widespread.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Around the year 1922, the first carrier frequency systems began to operate over high-tension lines with frequencies of 15 to 500 kHz for telemetry purposes, and this continues.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Consumer products such as baby alarms have been available at least since 1940.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In the 1930s, ripple carrier signaling was introduced on the medium (10–20 kV) and low voltage (240/415 V) distribution systems.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] For many years, the search continued for a cheap bi-directional technology suitable for applications such as remote meter reading.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] French electric power *Électricité de France* (EDF) prototyped and standardized a system called spread frequency shift keying or S-FSK.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] (See IEC 61334) It is now a simple, low-cost system with a long history, however it has a very slow transmission rate.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In the 1970s, the Tokyo Electric Power Company ran experiments that reported successful bidirectional operation with several hundred units.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] As of 2012 the system was widely used in Italy and some other parts of the EU.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] S-FSK sends a burst of 2, 4 or 8 tones centered around the time when the AC line passes through zero voltage.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In this way, the tones avoid most radio-frequency noise from arcing.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Different districts use different tone pairs to avoid interference.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The bit timing is typically recovered from the boundaries between tones, in a way similar to a UART.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Timing is roughly centered on the zero crossing with a timer from the previous zero crossing.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Typical speeds are 200 to 1200 bits per second, with one bit per tone slot.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Speeds also depend on the AC line frequency.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The speed is limited by noise and the jitter of the AC line's zero crossing, which is affected by local loads.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These systems are usually bidirectional, with both meters and central stations sending data and commands.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Higher levels of the protocols can have stations (usually smart meters) retransmit messages.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Since the mid-1980s, there has been a surge of interest in using the potential of digital communications techniques and digital signal processing.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The drive is to produce a reliable system that is cheap enough to be widely installed and able to compete cost effectively with wireless solutions.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] But the narrowband powerline communications channel presents many technical challenges, a mathematical channel model and a survey of work is available.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Applications of mains communications vary enormously, as would be expected of such a widely available medium.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] One natural application of narrow-band power-line communication is the control and telemetry of electrical equipment such as meters, switches, heaters and domestic appliances.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A number of active developments are considering such applications from a systems point of view, such as demand side management.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In this, domestic appliances would intelligently coordinate their use of resources, for example, limiting peak loads.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Control and telemetry applications include both *utility side* applications, which involve equipment belonging to the utility company up to the domestic meter, and *consumer-side* applications, which involve equipment in the consumer's premises.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Possible utility-side applications include automatic meter reading (AMR), dynamic tariff control, load management, load profile recording, credit control, pre-payment, remote connection, fraud detection and network management, and could be extended to include gas and water.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is one of the most proven narrowband PLC technologies and protocols for smart metering.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] There are, as of 2019, more than five million smart meters, based on OSGP and using BPSK PLC, installed and operating around the world .
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The OSGP Alliance led an effort to establish a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart grid applications.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] OSGP provides a delivery of command and control information for smart meters, direct load control modules, solar panels, gateways, and other smart grid devices.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] OSGP follows a modern, structured approach based on the OSI protocol model to meet the evolving challenges of the smart grid.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] At the physical layer, OSGP currently uses ETSI 103 908 as its technology standard.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This uses binary phase shift keying at 3592.98 BAUD, using a carrier tone of 86.232 KHz ± 200ppm.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This standard and command system provides not only for smart meters and related data but also for general-purpose extension to other smart grid devices.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A project of EDF, France, includes demand management, street lighting control, remote metering and billing, customer-specific tariff optimization, contract management, expense estimation and gas applications safety.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] There are also many specialized niche applications that use the mains supply within the home as a convenient data link for telemetry.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] For example, in the UK and Europe, a TV audience monitoring system uses powerline communications as a convenient data path between devices that monitor TV viewing activity in different rooms in a home and a data concentrator which is connected to a telephone modem.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The Distribution Line Carrier (DLC) System technology used a frequency range of 9 to 500 kHz with a data rate up to 576 kbit/s.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] A project called Real-time Energy Management via Powerlines and Internet (REMPLI) was funded from 2003 to 2006 by the European Commission.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] More modern systems use OFDM to send data at faster bit rates without causing radio frequency interference.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These utilize hundreds of slowly-sending data channels.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Usually, they can adapt to noise by turning off channels with interference.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The extra expense of the encoding devices is minor compared to the cost of the electronics to transmit.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The transmission electronics is usually a high-power operational amplifier, a coupling transformer and a power supply.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Similar transmission electronics is required on older, slower systems, so with improved technology, improved performance can be very affordable.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In 2009, a group of vendors formed the PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution (PRIME) alliance.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] As delivered, the physical layer is OFDM, sampled at 250 kHz, with 512 differential phase-shift keying channels from 42–89 kHz.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Its fastest transmission rate is 128.6 kbit/s, while its most robust is 21.4 kbit/s.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] It uses a convolutional code for error detection and correction.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In 2011, several companies including distribution network operators (ERDF, Enexis), meter vendors (Sagemcom, Landis&Gyr) and chip vendors (Maxim Integrated, Texas Instruments, STMicroelectronics, Renesas) founded the G3-PLC Alliance to promote G3-PLC technology.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] G3-PLC is the low-layer protocol to enable large-scale infrastructure on the electrical grid.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] G3-PLC may operate on CENELEC A band (35 to 91 kHz) or CENELEC B band (98 kHz to 122 kHz) in Europe, on ARIB band (155 kHz to 403 kHz) in Japan and on FCC (155 kHz to 487 kHz) for the US and the rest of the world.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The technology used is OFDM sampled at 400 kHz with adaptive modulation and tone mapping.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Error detection and correction are made by both a convolutional code and Reed-Solomon error correction.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The required media access control is taken from IEEE 802.15.4, a radio standard.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In the protocol, 6loWPAN has been chosen to adapt IPv6, an internet network layer, to the constrained environments of power line communications.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] 6loWPAN integrates routing, based on the mesh network LOADng, header compression, fragmentation and security.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] G3-PLC has been designed for extremely robust communication based on reliable and highly secure connections between devices, including crossing Medium Voltage to Low Voltage transformers.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] With the use of IPv6, G3-PLC enables communication between meters, grid actuators as well as smart objects.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In December 2011, G3 PLC technology was recognized as an international standard at ITU in Geneva where it is referenced as G.9903, Narrowband orthogonal frequency division multiplexing power line communication transceivers for G3-PLC networks.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Sometimes, PLC was used for transmitting radio programs over powerlines.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] When operated in the AM radio band, it is known as a carrier current system.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] High-frequency communication may (re)use large portions of the radio spectrum for communication, or may use select (narrow) band(s), depending on the technology.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power line communications can also be used in a home to interconnect home computers and peripherals, and home entertainment devices that have an Ethernet port.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Powerline adapter sets plug into power outlets to establish an Ethernet connection using the existing electrical wiring in the home (power strips with filtering may absorb the power line signal).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This allows devices to share data without the inconvenience of running dedicated network cables.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The widely deployed powerline networking standards are from Nessum Alliance and HomePlug Powerline Alliance.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] HomePlug Powerline Alliance announced in October 2016 that it would wind down its activities, and the Alliance website (homeplug.org) has been closed.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Nessum (formerly HD-PLC), and HomePlug AV, which is the most current of the HomePlug specifications, were adopted by the IEEE 1901 group as baseline technologies for their standard, published 30 December 2010.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] HomePlug estimates that over 45 million HomePlug devices have been deployed worldwide.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Other companies and organizations back different specifications for power line home networking, and these include the Universal Powerline Association, SiConnect, Xsilon, and the ITU-T's G.hn (HomeGrid) specification.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] With the diversification of IoT applications, the demand for high-speed data communication such as transmission of high-definition video data or high-frequency sensor data is increasing in the field of smart building, smart factory, smart city, etc.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In such use cases, power line communication technologies can also be used and provide the same advantage of reusing existing cables.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Nessum has developed a multi-hop technology that can be used to build large-scale networks.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In addition, the latest Nessum technology (4th-generation HD-PLC technology) provides multiple channels, which enable high-speed and long-range communication by selecting the optimal channel.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Broadband over power line (BPL) is a system to transmit two-way data over existing AC MV (medium voltage) electrical distribution wiring, between transformers, and AC LV (low voltage) wiring between transformer and customer outlets (typically 100 to 240 V).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This avoids the expense of a dedicated network of wires for data communication, and the expense of maintaining a dedicated network of antennas, radios and routers in a wireless network.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] BPL uses some of the same radio frequencies used for over-the-air radio systems.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Modern BPL employs Wavelet-OFDM, FFT-OFDM, or frequency-hopping spread spectrum to avoid using those frequencies actually in use, though early pre-2010 BPL standards did not.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The criticisms of BPL from this perspective are of pre-OPERA, pre-1905 standards.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The BPL OPERA standard is used primarily in Europe by ISPs.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In North America, it is used in some places (Washington Island, WI, for instance) but is more generally used by electric distribution utilities for smart meters and load management.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Even higher information rate transmissions over power line use RF through microwave frequencies transmitted via a transverse mode surface wave propagation mechanism that requires only a single conductor.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] An implementation of this technology is marketed as E-Line.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These use microwaves instead of the lower frequency bands, up to 2–20 GHz.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] While these may interfere with radio astronomy when used outdoors, the advantages of speeds competitive with fiber optic cables without new wiring are likely to outweigh that.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] These systems claim symmetric and full duplex communication in excess of 1 Gbit/s in each direction.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Multiple Wi-Fi channels with simultaneous analog television in the 2.4 and 5.0 GHz unlicensed bands have been demonstrated operating over a single medium voltage line conductor.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Because the underlying propagation mode is extremely broadband (in the technical sense), it can operate anywhere in the 20 MHz to 20 GHz region.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Also, since it is not restricted to below 80 MHz, as is the case for high-frequency BPL, these systems can avoid the interference issues associated with the use of shared spectrum with other licensed or unlicensed services.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Two distinctly different sets of standards apply to powerline networking as of early 2010.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Within homes, the IEEE 1901 standards specify how, globally, existing AC wires should be employed for data purposes.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The IEEE 1901 includes Nessum and HomePlug AV as baseline technologies.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Any IEEE 1901 products can coexist and be fully interoperable between products using the same technology.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] On the other hand, medium-frequency home control devices remain divided, although X10 tends to be dominant.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] For power grid use, IEEE has approved a low-frequency (≤ 500 kHz) standard called IEEE 1901.2 in 2013.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Several competing organizations have developed specifications, including the HomePlug Powerline Alliance (defunct), Universal Powerline Association (defunct), and Nessum Alliance (active).
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In October 2009, the ITU-T adopted Recommendation G.hn/G.9960 as a standard of networks for high-speed powerline, coax, and phoneline communications.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The National Energy Marketers Association (a US trade body) was also involved in advocating for standards.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] In July 2009, the IEEE Power Line Communication Standards Committee approved its draft standard for broadband over power lines.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The IEEE 1901 final standard was published on 30 December 2010, and included features from HomePlug and Nessum.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Power line communication via IEEE 1901 and IEEE 1905 compliant devices is indicated by the nVoy certification all major vendors of such devices committed to in 2013.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] NIST has included IEEE 1901 (Nessum, HomePlug AV) and ITU-T G.hn as "Additional Standards Identified by NIST Subject to Further Review" for the Smart grid in the United States.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] IEEE also came up with a low-frequency standard for long-distance smart grids called IEEE 1901.2 in 2013.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] PLC technology is widely used in the following systems to empower Smart Building, Smart Factory, Smart Grid, and Smart City, etc., as a solution to reduce network construction costs.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] The primary challenge with the PLC to date is the unshielded and untwisted power wiring.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] This type of wiring releases significant radio energy, potentially disrupting others using the same frequency band.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Additionally, the BPL (Broadband over Power Line) systems may experience interference from the radio signals produced by the PLC wiring.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] For home networks relying on powerline communication technology, how to deal with electrical noise injected into the system from standard household appliances remains the largest challenge.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] Whenever any appliance is turned on or turned off it creates noise that could possibly disrupt data transfer through the wiring.
[src:lonworks/power-line-communication] IEEE products that are certified to be HomePlug 1.0 compliant have been engineered to no longer interfere with, or receive interference from other devices plugged into the same home's electrical grid.
